      <Property Name="Text">Remark</Property>
    </Object>
    <Object Type="Vector.CANalyzer.Panels.Design.StaticTextControl, Vector.CANalyzer.Panels.CommonControls, Version=18.0.150.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null" Name="StaticTextControl5" ControlName="Static Text 2">
      <Property Name="Name">StaticTextControl5</Property>
      <Property Name="Size">656, 65</Property>
      <Property Name="Location">20, 769</Property>
      <Property Name="BackColor">HighlightText</Property>
      <Property Name="Text">It is obvious that CANoe has to run in order to run a simulation!
But in a real measurement environment with real HW, there might be the need of a signal indicating that CANoe is running.
The DUT might check such a signal in order to remind the user to start CANoe before measuring.
To simulate this behavior, it is helpful to mimic a halted CANoe by using the state CANoe Running = OFF.
'CANoe running' is realized as a static output of the VIO System's VIO4028 card.</Property>
    </Object>
    <Object Type="Vector.CANalyzer.Panels.Design.StaticTextControl, Vector.CANalyzer.Panels.CommonControls, Version=18.0.150.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null" Name="StaticTextControl6" ControlName="Static Text 3">
      <Property Name="Name">StaticTextControl6</Property>
      <Property Name="Size">554, 276</Property>
      <Property Name="Location">20, 34</Property>
      <Property Name="BackColor">HighlightText</Property>
      <Property Name="Text">The CANoe Dashboard consists of...

A CANoe start button to virtually start/stop CANoe (see remark below).

A slider to set the counter speed.
-This slider generates an analog voltage that is read by the DUT in order to set the 4-bit counter speed.
- Voltage range 0..10V
- Speed range 2..20 Hz

Two indicators showing the counter value and the counter frequency.
- The frequency is calculated by doubling the input frequency of bit 0 of the counter.

A slider to control the analog dimmable LED on the DUT.
- This slider generates an analog voltage that directyl goes to the analog dimmable LED.

Two indicators showing the analog LED voltage and current.
- The current is taken from a value table as no real LED exists.

Two indicators showing the PWM dimmable LED's control voltage and duty cycle.
- The voltage comes from the slider on the DUT.
- The duty cycle is calculated and sent to the LED via the VIO4028 PWM output.
</Property>
    </Object>
